<section xml:id="section-motivating-problems">
  <title>Motivating Problems</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      To motivate the course, I want to describe a few important
      problems which cannot be solved just with algebra. I hope these
      seem practical and worthwhile to you, so that it makes sense why
      we would need to develop a whole new kind of mathematics to
      solve these problems. To recap from the last section, I want to
      describe the (quantitative) world. I observe that in the world,
      quantities are interrelated and interdependent. These quantities
      are also dynamic, constantly in flux. To make a mathematical
      description of the world, the description must also be dynamic
      and interdependant.  That requires functions, and calculus is
      the study of their dynamic behaviour. Here are some such dynamic
      problems.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-motivating-population">
    <title>Motivating Problem: Population Growth</title>
    <p>
      If I observe a population (human, animal, plant, etc.) over
      time, one of most common behaviours to observe is percentage
      growth. A population increase (or decrease) over a fixed
      period of time usually depends on how large the population is,
      and that dependence is very commonly a percentage. In Canada,
      for example, the population growth over the last few decades
      has usually been between one and three percent. Percentages
      make sense for populattion growth: a larger population can
      produce more offspring, and under consistent conditions, will
      produce offspring at some consistent rate. That's a
      percentage.
    </p>
    <p>
      At a fixed point in time, algebra can, of course, just
      calculate this percetage. 
      If I have a population of 7 million and a percentage growth
      of  <m>1.7\%</m> per year, then I can just calculate that the
      population will increase by <m>119,000</m> individuals. This
      is algebra, but this is only a single calculation. It tells me
      the growth at a moment, but no more. 
    </p>
    <p>
      What if I wanted a more holistic picture? What is I wanted a
      <em>function</em> that describes the popluation over time?
      This algebra cannot solve. Percentage growth descripes a
      growth rate of a function. But it doesn't tell you what the
      function actually is. To find the function, you need a
      mathematical method to start with a growth rate and produce
      the original function. That's the kind of dynamic problem
      that algebra can't solve.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is a pretty universal problem: it doesn't just apply to
      population. Anything that is described by a growth rate has
      this problem: how do you get to a function when you know only
      the growth rate. This situation arises in many contexts: rates
      of heating and cooling; rates of financial or economic growth;
      rates of production of a new chemical in a chemical reaction;
      rates of radio-active decay; I could go on. That said, I
      choose population because of its importance, and because it is a
      biological problem.  Historically (as I will discuss shortly),
      biology was not the motivating context for the invention of
      the calculus. But population dynamics in biology is a perfect
      environment to demonstrate the value of calculus. Throughout
      this course, I'll rely most heavily on population dynamics as
      motivation: I want this to be a course about understanding the
      nature of population growth and how it can be reasonably
      described mathematically. 
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-motivating-velocity">
    <title>Motivating Problem: Velocity</title>
    <figure xml:id="figure-slope-linear">
      <caption>Slope of a Linear Function</caption>
      <image xml:id="figure10" width="60%">
        <asymptote>
          size(10cm);

          import graph;

          xaxis("$t$");
          yaxis("$p$");

          real f(real x) {return x/3;}

          draw(graph(f,0,8));

          draw((6,2)--(6,1)--(3,1));

          label("rise",(6,1.5),E);
          label("run",(4.5,1),S);
          label("$a =$ slope",(4.5,1.5),NW);
          label("$p=at$", (8,8/3),E);
        </asymptote>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      My first example was biological. However, the history of
      calculus comes more from physics and geometry. So, let me go
      back to that history. Coming from physics, I'll start with the
      velocity problem.  Assume there is an object moving in one
      dimension. I can describe its position as a function
      <m>p(t)</m> where <m>p</m> is position in terms of time
      <m>t</m>. I want to know its velocity.
    </p>
    <p>
      If <m>p(t) = at + b</m> is a linear function, then algebra can
      answer this question. With this linear function, for each unit
      of time the object travels <m>a</m> units of distance. In
      <xref ref="figure-slope-linear" />, units of time are in the
      horizontal direction (the run) and units of position are in
      the vertical direction (the rise). The value <m>a</m> is the
      velocity. Geometrically, the velocity is measured by the slope
      of the straight line graph of <m>p(t)</m>, which you may
      remember from high school as `rise over run'. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Slope is easy for a linear function: such functions represent
      constant velocity. But with most moving objects, velocity is
      not constant. The graph of a function where velocity is
      non-constant is not a straight line.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="figure-tangent-line">
      <caption>Non-Constant Velocity</caption>
      <image xml:id="figure11" width="60%">
        <asymptote>
          size(10cm);

          import graph;

          xaxis("$x$");
          yaxis("$y$");

          real f1(real x) {return (x^3-x^2+x+1)/8;}
          real f2(real x) {return 3/8*x - 11/76;}

          draw(graph(f1,0,2.2));
          draw(graph(f2,0,3));
        </asymptote>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      How do we figure out the velocity of a function whose graph is
      not a straight line?  The line drawn in <xref
      ref="figure-tangent-line"/> is called a tangent line. It just
      touches the graph at one points. It's a straight line, so it
      has a slope, and therefore a velocity.  Finding this slope
      would be a way to understand the velocity of this object. 
    </p>
    <p>
      But wow do I calculate a tangent line? Algebra has trouble
      with this problem. All I have is a point and the function.
      There is no second point with which to define a line and thus
      a slope. So here is another problem to motivate calculus.
      Geometrically, how can I find the slope of a tangent line? In
      terms of movement, how can I determine the velocity of a
      function which measure position. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Like growth rates, there are many version of this problem.
      For anything that changes in time, I can ask how fast it is
      changing. The velocity problem deals with position over time,
      but indeed any function of time leads to the same question.
      If heat depends on time, how fast is the heat increasing or
      decreasing? If happiness depends on time, how fast is
      happiness increasing or decreasing? This is all essentially
      the same motivating problem: finding the rate of change given
      a function that depends on time. 
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-motivating-distance">
    <title>Motivating Problem: Distance Travelled</title>
    <p>
      Now I will consider the opposite problem. Consider a function
      <m>v(t)</m> which tells me the velocity of an object at any
      point of time. How can I determine the distance the object has
      covered over a period of time? Again, in the special situation
      where the velocity is constant, algebra can solve this. 
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="figure-constant-velocity">
      <caption>Constant Velocity</caption>
      <image xml:id="figure14" width="60%">
        <asymptote>
          size(10cm);

          import graph;

          xaxis("$t$");
          yaxis("$y$");

          draw((0,4)--(6,4)--(6,0));
          
          label("$v(t) = c$",(3,4),N);

          dot("$t=0$",(0,0),NE);
          dot("$t=t_0$",(6,0),NW);

          label("Area$",(2,2),E);
        </asymptote>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      If velocity is constant, then I am moving at some fixed number
      $c$ units of distance per unit of time. If I multiply $c$ by
      the time, I get the distance. Travelling at 40 km/h for 3
      hours means you have travelled <m>40 \cdot 3 = 120</m>km.
      Algebra can do this. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Geometrically, in <xref ref="figure-constant-velocity"/>, the
      velociy is the height of the graph and the time is the witdh.
      The product of the two is height times width, which is just
      area. The velocity travelled is the area under the velocity
      graph. 
    </p>
    <p>
      If the velocity is non-constant, then I get a more complicated
      graph in <xref ref="figure-non-constant-velocity"/>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="figure-non-constant-velocity">
      <caption>Non-Constant Velocity</caption>
      <image xml:id="figure15" width="60%">
        <asymptote>
          size(10cm);

          import graph;

          xaxis("$x$");
          yaxis("$y$");

          draw((0,3){SE}..{E}(2,1.6){E}..{NE}(4,4){NE}..{SE}(6,3));
          draw((6,3)--(6,0));

          label("$v(t)$",(3,3),N);

          dot("$t=0$",(0,0),NE);
          dot("$t=t_0$",(6,0),NW);
          
          label("Area = Distance Travelled",(0.2,1),E);
        </asymptote>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The distance travelled is still the area underneath this
      graph, just as it was for constant velocity.  Therefore, to
      solve the distance travelled problem, I need to find areas
      under graphs like these. Liketangent lines, this is not a
      problem that algebra can easily tackle. This is a complicated
      area under a curving path: there is no easy formula for
      algebra to apply. 
    </p>
    <p>
      This is the third motivating problem. Geometrically, given a
      graph, can I calculate the area underneath the graph? In physics
      terms, this means starting with a velocity function and
      determining the total distance travelled. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Like the two previous problem, there are many versions of this
      problem. Velociy measures how fast your are travelling, so
      distance travelled is the total <sq>work</sq> accomplished by
      travelling. Anytime I consider a function which directly
      describes a rate of something being accomplish, then the area
      under that curve is the total amount of <sq>work</sq>
      accomplished by that function. If I have a function that
      measures the rate of water usage in a population, the area is
      the total amount of water consumed. If I have a funciton that
      measures the interest rate on a bank account, then the area is
      the total amount of interest gained. I could go on: any
      <sq>work accomplished</sq> probelm also fits this pattern. And
      for any of these problems, if the situation is non-linear, I
      need new techique beyond algebra to solve it. 
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-motivating-optmization">
    <title>Motivating Problem: Optimization</title>
    <p>
      The previous three motivating problems were direct: they all
      were about some kind of specific calculation or the production
      of a specific function. The fourth is a little indirect, but
      still very important. 
    </p>
    <p>
      An optimization problem is any problem that asks for some
      superlative: the best, worse, highest, lowest, etc. This is
      applied to some function by asking <sq>When is the function at
      its highest peak or lowest valley?</sq> This is, again, a
      problem that algebra has a hard time with. Visually, the
      problem is easy: if you can see the function, you can just
      point out the peaks and the valleys. 
    </p>
    <p>
      But it turns out that calculating peaks and valleys percisely
      is quite difficult and algebra fails, in general, to do this.
      Peaks and valleys are parts of the changing dynamics of the
      fuction and the difficult in finding these points is similar
      to finding tangent lines and areas under curves. It turns out
      we need the same tools<mdash/>we need calculus. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Obviously, optimization is a pretty valuable kind of problem
      fo solve. The world is full of people looking for optimal
      solutions. Whenever the optimization situation it described
      using function, these problem solving are using calculus.
      Solving optimization problems turns out to be one of the major
      reasons that calculus is so useful and important. 
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
